Republican Strategy for Resistance to Re-election of Obama
Republican leaders justified their policy by the need to combat election frauds.
However, the Brennan Center considers the last myth, claiming that cases of falsifications in the United States are more rare than deaths from lightning.
In addition, the Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of electoral frauds in the United States in ten years.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this regard, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
Unlike Canada, American states are responsible for organizing federal elections in the United States.
That is why most state governments have passed laws that complicate the process of registration or voting since 2009.
This phenomenon gained a new scale after the elections in November 2010, which brought to the Republicans 675 new places in 26 states.
As a result, in one 2011, 180 bills were adopted, limiting the right to vote in 41 states.
New electoral laws require the electorate to present an identity card with a photo and proof of the existence of American citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce the period of early voting, abolish the right to register a voter on the day of expression and take away the right to vote from citizens who have a conviction.
Before the 2006 elections, no American state obliged voters to present an identity card with a photo.
Indiana was the first state to impose such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court confirmed in 2008 the constitutionality of the law adopted in Indiana.
The Republican authorities hurried to extend this practice to other states as well.
In the last two years, they initiated bills requiring voters to present identity cards with photography, in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike Quebec, American citizens do not have such a universal identity card as a card of health insurance.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, i.e. 21 million people who have reached the required age for voting, do not have a photo ID issued by the government body of their state.
In addition, five million new voters in 2012 do not have such a document.
At the same time, the cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds one hundred dollars.
New restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and low-income people.
In fact, 25% of African Americans, 15% of people earning less than $ 35,000, 18% of citizens over 65 years old and 20% of voters from 18 to 29 years do not have the required identity card with photography.
But that's not all.
Students - voters who are considered to vote for democratic candidates, in several states are not allowed to use the identity card with a photo given by their educational institution.
But these same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mainly for Republicans, to use certificates issued by these clubs for voting.
Until 2004, no state demanded evidence of American citizenship for voting.
For the first time such a requirement was introduced in Arizona.
Since 2011, more than ten states have passed laws requiring voters to prove that they are citizens of the United States.
These measures are obviously aimed at limiting the vote of natives from Latin America.
It is believed that two-thirds of Latin American voters vote in favor of the Democratic Party.
In addition, the republican legislators initiated in 2011 laws abolishing the registration of voters on voting day in eight states.
They also restricted the right of individuals or groups to assist those who wish to register.
This restriction has not passed without consequences.
For example, during the 2004 elections, the electoral registration campaign helped to include about 10 million citizens on the lists.
At the same time, the measures taken since 2009 led to a drop of 17% of the level of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, the republican legislators adopted in five other states laws aimed at reducing the period of early voting.
Thus, during the general elections of 2008 in Florida, 33% of voters who voted early were African Americans, although the latter accounted for only 13% of the total number of voters in the state.
The same happened to the natives of Latin America.
Representing only 11% of voters, they accounted for 24% of citizens who voted ahead of schedule.
Unlike the Whites, which, forming 76% of the voters, were only 46% of the voters who voted ahead of schedule.
Of course, the legislators-democrats and their supporters actively oppose the adoption of laws restricting the registration of voters.
Several draft laws were vetoed by democrat governors.
The action of the most ambiguous laws was suspended when the United States Prosecutor General intervened.
This allowed to partially limit the negative consequences.
For example, only 16 out of 34 states adopted laws requiring presentation of an identity card with a photo.
Nevertheless, the new rules that have come into force will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote at the 2012 elections.
Critics from the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that have been adopted, seeing in them an obvious focus on influencing the results of the 2012 elections in key states.
The 2011 report of the Brennan Center demonstrates that the states that adopted these laws represent 171 out of 270 votes needed at the board of electors to win the presidential elections.
It is too early to assert with confidence that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the results of the presidential elections of 2012.
Only one thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this regard, such actions partially discredit the system of American democracy.
