In the shelter of Victor-Gadbua no one day is similar to the previous one.
Next to the 93-year-old, who enjoys his last meeting with his family in the yard, sitting on his pillows while toast in his honor, tragically dies young man 36 years old, surrounded by parents, wife and two young children and tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months from three to five beds, always engaged in cancer patients under the age of 45," says Dr. Christian Martel.
53% of patients accepted in the shelter Victor-Gadbua arrive from home, and 47% of the hospital.
The problem of accessing palliative care
It is believed that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, that is, to care, to alleviate the suffering of the sick who entered the final stage of their lives, whether at home, in the hospital or in the shelter.
And some institutions, such as the shelter of Victor-Gadbua and the Society of Palliative Care at the Big Montreal House, specialize more or less exclusively in the care of cancer patients.
It is this large gap in the health system of Quebec that makes many doctors - specialists in palliative care to fear the adoption of the law legalizing euthanasia and assistance in suicide.
Since October, the manifesto has been circulating, signed by the luminaries in palliative care, Dr. Balfuhr Hamunt and Dr. Bernard Lyapuant and testifying to their disagreement with this initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, the Québec health system is not effective enough to ensure the right to palliative care of high quality before the transition to euthanasia is allowed.
Recently," she says, "I saw a patient who spent 14 days in the ambulance department, in terrible pains, and no one has taken the necessary measures to alleviate them.
I am afraid that patients want to die only because they do not get adequate care.
At the same time, many oncologists until the last day try to save patients, despite pessimistic forecasts.
The hopes of survival of Helen Richard were already minimal when she stopped exhausting chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regrets that I was stopping fighting," she says.
At the same time, she told me myself that my days were numbered!
There is no omnipotent care
Dr. Martel believes that 90% of patients who ask for death thank the medical staff for failing to fulfill their request, after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not absolutely omnipotent in the fight against pain.
According to Elsi Monroe, director of palliative care at the Grand Montreal House Palliative Care Society, patients are not susceptible to anesthesia in 8% of cases.
At the very end of life, doctors often resort to palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps to the moment of his death, either from time to time or constantly.
One cannot pretend more that we do not know about these sufferings.
Increasingly, patients who are unable to relieve pain will be able to have access to palliative sedation.
Patients suffering from pain always say the same phrase: "I want to die."
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want me to have euthanasia," which means "I want me to make it easier for me."
