The bitcoin exchange rate, reaching a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, fell five months later to 2 dollars before returning today to about ten dollars (courses listed on the website bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special in comparison with the world exchange of real money or financial products.
However, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on the virtual currency, published in October, was interested in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency," "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "like ordinary currencies."
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currencies as "credits" used to promote in video games that are earned during the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchange).
Social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange operations always control and process any central authority.
In Bitcoin, all network nodes are simultaneously holders of the book, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Each transaction between the two users actually occurs between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
A set of information relating to this transaction is signed electronically, using a dual-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Thanks to the contents of the file, it is possible to check that the bitcoins used in the deal do exist in the public account book sent across the network.
The key stage is the registration of a new transaction in this book.
It goes through the solution of the mathematical problem sent to computers, which, as if a temporary central bank, gets the privilege to add this new line.
We are talking about the phase of hashes the file, that is, the conversion of a large file into a digital signature, short and unique.
Computers "take" a new transaction and add a number to it, before "shock" all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once this number is found, other nodes easily check that it is correct.
Transaction thus turns out to be an unracing-related chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If for the purpose of cheating the user very quickly (less than ten minutes) would like to pay twice the same topic and the same money, only one of these two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, as they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem receives 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the award is regularly divided in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divided to one stomillion, which leaves the reserve...
The complexity of the task also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the network has already experienced ups and downs.
The websites providing bitcoin services were attacked and bitcoins were stolen from reserves.
"The defect used does not concern the protocol itself," says Pierre Nuaz, who recently launched Paymium - a company making payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported on the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
Large players, such as Wikipedia, refuse to accept donations of this kind.
Others, such as the WordPress blog platform, allow them.
Recently, Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron from the Weizman Institute in Israel analyzed the counting book and found that almost 80% of Bitcoins are not in circulation.
"Giant sales" were announced in November.
"Thirty thousand dollars have been exchanged," Joan Holmkwist, who works in Coinabul, who converts bitcoins into gold, rejoices.
Pierre Nuaz, another author of the manual on this currency, firmly believes in the potential of this technology as an operating network.
Its system, Paytunia, is the equivalent of a credit card (in real money) or contactless payment via mobile phone, but it uses bitcoin to check transactions that is thus cheaper.
The holder controls his/her personal data better and can thus be anonymous.
The system is simple to implement for entrepreneurs who do not need to install new devices or software.
It is enough to only inform the address that you can "photograph and recognize" the phone, specifies Pierre Noise, assuring that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general trend of revising hierarchical systems in favor of more horizontal.
"Before Bitcoin will be affirmed, it will take some time, but 2013 may be a turning point," he predicts.
The ECB in its report suggests, by the way, to reconsider a variety of risks, which are considered today increased, in case of the success of this system.
