My crisis of national self-determination is the American story of Mexican origin.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico because of the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the inhabitants of the country of difficult times.
Ruben Navarette believes that American Mexicans are torn apart between two cultures.
During my recent trip to Mexico City, I walked along the corridor for arriving, approached the border control zone and frozen on the spot.
The signs were indicated in two queues: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the second for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I was called a Mexican all my life.
This is just a conditional name, just like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and friends from New York consider themselves Italians.
Later I stopped at the complex construction of "American Mexican origin."
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in the homeland of my grandfather, there was no need for conditional names or complex structures.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than native speakers, and I can't get rid of the American accent.
That's why I got my American passport and became in turn for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago, when the newly elected president of Mexico, Enrique Pena Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda included the usual issues of these countries' meetings: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Penha Nieto was willing to talk about the rise of the Mexican economy, thanks to which the Mexicans will now be able to stay in Mexico with the same success, instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to conclude a partnership agreement with the United States and Canada and create a North American trade block like the European Union.
In addition, President Penha Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, the relationship with the United States is a difficult and executed old offense question.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848 the United States invaded Mexico and forced its leaders to abandon half of their territory under the barrel of rifles.
But Mexicans think for centuries, not minutes, and see reminders of those events in everything.
Therefore, it is necessary only to any U.S. state official to speak at least a word of criticism towards Mexico, in the press and among the elite of the Mexican society immediately complain that the Americans are infringing on the sovereignty of neighbors.
And the descendants of Montesium are filled with militantness.
At the same time, the most difficult are the relations of Mexico with more than 35 million Americans of Mexican origin living in the United States.
Would you like to talk about offenses?
They are enough.
In Mexico there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country for themselves, and those for whom there are no such opportunities.
In Los Angeles, Las Vegas, Phoenix, Denver or San Antonio so many people of Mexican origin for only one reason: at some point in their family history, someone - father or grandfather - had no opportunity to realize himself in Mexico and was forced to go north.
Most often they were Mexicans of a certain type - swarthy, uneducated, poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today our life is the embodiment of the American dream, we studied in good schools and settled for good works, but we do not forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national self-determination is confusing and unclear, but we know what country to consider its own.
United States of America.
In addition, we know that most representatives of the Mexican elite and the ruling class do not like us.
We answer them the same.
They see in us a reminder of humiliating lesions and treat us as people of the second grade, as not real Mexicans.
We speak Spanish not well enough, and our ties with Mexico are not strong enough.
Our very existence is due to failures for them.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We would not be behind the silk curtain, finding a full life in the United States, but losing spiritual ties.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and legally moved to the United States as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between the real Mexicans and Americans of Mexican origin - Mexicans understand their national identity, and Americans of Mexican origin it is offensive.
She is a US citizen and believes that it belongs to both of these countries.
At the same time, many of my acquaintance Americans of Mexican origin do not feel belonging to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but also love Bruce Springstin.
When you get the best of the two worlds, you inevitably lose your root.
In Mexico we are Americans.
And in the United States we are called Mexicans.
Now, as I found out during my trip, as if our relations are not enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to restore relations with the diaspora.
They want Americans of Mexican origin to work as ambassadors of Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country it is and how great it is to visit it, and could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
Nothing will come out.
Too much offense in the past.
And given the gap between the rich and the poor, the spread of corruption and drug trafficking, many of us do not consider this country so beautiful.
Sorry, but deal with it yourself, amigos.
And this is true.
If some Mexicans still can't forgive the United States how they did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Americans of Mexican origin are still in resentment for how recently they dealt with their relatives in Mexico.
Yes.
Perhaps we have more in common than it seemed to me.
Old battles in the new Middle East
The ceasefire agreement between Israel and Hamas may become a fragile foundation for further peace
Is there a long-term peace between the Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East?
The next round of bloodshed pushes to the conclusion about the futility of such hopes.
There are common, meaningless disputes about who the first started; many buildings have been turned into ruins; more than 140 Palestinians have been killed, most of whom were civilians, and six Israelis; for the first time during the conflict, rockets fired from the Gaza Strip have fallen in the vicinity of the capital of Israel, Tel Aviv and the sacred city of Jerusalem.
However, despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly tied up in their eternal conflict, changes have come to the Middle East.
This can be treated differently, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have swirled in a rebellious storm of established realities, and the Palestinians and Israelis have failed to stay away from the vortex that shocked the region.
Perhaps as a result, their struggle will become even more bloody than before.
However, there are reasons that give hope to get out of this deadly deadlock.
War without winners
At first glance, the current situation does not give any reason for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire, which was signed on November 21, the clashes that took place this week only strengthened the positions of the security forces on both sides.
The leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, who came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, will declare that they forced Israel to retreat despite their losses.
Despite the fact that some leaders of the group were destroyed, and 1.7 million residents are blocked in one of the most densely populated and problematic corners of our planet, Israel failed to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing its popularity in the West Bank - another Palestinian territory controlled by the currently more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time works for them.
As the influence of Islamist movements in the Arab world grows, Hamas has new influential and rich friends.
The reviving regional leader of Turkey, who once was Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, supported Hamas; its example was followed by Qatar, one of the richest and most dynamically developing countries in the Persian Gulf.
The ceasing supporters of Hamas declare the creation of an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, in which the paramilitary group of Hezbollah rule, to Syria, in which increasingly the Islamic rebels are about to overthrow Bashar al-Assad's power, and then to Jordan, where the king's authorities are threatening the allies of Hamas.
The most significant change in the balance of forces in the region occurred on the southern borders of Israel, in the most populous and important Arab country, in Egypt, where under President Mohammed Mursi the influence of the Muslim Brotherhood was strengthened.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was overthrown in 2011, was a secular dictator who did not pay much attention to the support of Hamas.
The Muslim brothers, on the contrary, are an organization similar to Hamas, and their leaders are more prone to populism.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas can become a significant player whose voice will not be able to stifle even to Israel and America.
At the same time, supporters of the "hard" line in Israel will come to opposite conclusions.
In the military sense, Hamas was defeated.
The Israeli missile system "Iron Dome" justified the cost of its creation and successfully destroyed many of the missiles launched by Hamas.
Citizens of Israel can sleep quietly, at least for some time.
As for diplomacy, the U.S. remained loyal to its unalterable position; many European countries also blamed the last round of violence on Hamas.
Another important factor is the economic prosperity of Israel, especially in the government of Binyamin Netanyahu, which largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the fact that since 2004. Approximately 30 Israelis died from missiles fired from the Gaza Strip, Israel managed to minimize the problem of suicide terrorists, partly at the expense of the wall that enters the West Bank of the Jordan River - a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions from the point of view of international law.
The position of Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party - in preparation for the January 22 elections - united with even more aggressive conservatives under the leadership of Avigdor Lieberman, is very convenient.
What is the point of indulging in the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If they give all power in the West Bank, will they not start launching missiles from there to Israel, as do their fellows in the Gaza Strip do?
It is better to keep them behind the wall and firmly suppress any attempts to raise their heads.
Perhaps the supporters of the "hard" line will win; but their calculations may be refuted by the Arab spring.
While the Islamists who come to power in Egypt and other countries do not feel the warmest feelings for Israel, their priority will be internal problems.
The defense part of Israel's budget is greater than all its Arab neighbors combined.
The unleashing of war with the regional superpower is unlikely to help the governments of the Arab countries to strengthen their own economy.
The pragmatism of the President of Egypt, Mursi, who together with Barack Obama worked on a ceasefire, is a good sign and can mark the beginning of change.
Israel, to no less, should take into account the long-term consequences of its policy.
As democratic changes in the Arab countries, the deprivation of the right to self-determination of Palestinians is a time bomb that will sooner or later explode in Israel's occupied territories, like a bus blown up in Tel Aviv this week.
Repressions already undermine the foundations of democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - only exacerbates these problems.
The bloody operations that take place every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress the Hamas movement have to pay the growing dissatisfaction of the international community.
Both sides need an external impulse
There is only a solution to which relentlessly call sane representatives on both sides, as well as most of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and concessions to Israel territories in exchange for security.
There is hope that not too impressive in the short term - the hope that the ceasefire will allow other countries to more effectively influence the parties of the conflict.
Egypt, which has long decided to block the supply of weapons to Gaza, as well as Turkey and Qatar have more than ever a favorable position to convince Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state adopted since 1967, taking into account the exchange of territories and the joint use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah's movements.
This would make more for the establishment of a Palestinian state than the upcoming vote at the UN, the result of which could be the recognition of the virtual statehood of Palestine.
President Obama must also play his role in seating Israel at the negotiating table.
During his first term, he did not present his own plan of peaceful settlement.
After returning to the White House, he still demonstrates his reluctance to connect to the solution of this problem.
This is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States is vitally interested in stability in the Middle East.
This is possible only in the case of a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
In Australia, the law on unified packaging for cigarettes came into force.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the images of body parts affected by diseases are contrastingly on dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
The first in the world practice Australian law on the same type of packaging of cigarettes and tobacco products came into force, replacing logos and color design of different brands of the same box of gloomy-olive color with terrible pictures of body parts affected by disease and images of children whose health is undermined by smoking of their parents.
In addition to different pictures and inscriptions warning of the dangers of smoking, the only difference between packs introduced mandatory from this Saturday - the names of brands that are printed in the same small font.
These are the most severe conditions in the world for the design of tobacco products packaging.
The Federal Government of Australia states that the purpose of this measure is to keep young people from smoking, depriving this harmful habit of fashion status.
Such a decision was based on the results of studies showing that people who did not start smoking up to 26 years, in 99 cases out of 100 never become smokers.
"It is obvious that even at the youngest age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through packaging," explains the Minister of Health Tanya Plibersec, referring to studies showing that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with children with the idea of a princess.
Australia is one of the countries with the world's smallest share of smokers, so these changes will not particularly affect the profits of multinational corporations, but the possibility of such measures is already considered by other countries.
Representatives of the tobacco industry strongly opposed the adoption of this law.
Tobacco companies claim that this will only increase the share of the black market, which will sell cheap and affordable cigarettes.
"This law will lead to serious consequences other than those that were conceived by its initiators," said Scott McIntayr, representative of British American Tobacco in Australia.
Forged producers from China and Indonesia will supply much more such goods for sale on the streets of Australia.
For someone, on the contrary, the new laws contribute to the growth of business.
Sandra Ha from a small family company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for portigars and silicone cases that hide unpleasant pictures on the package, has grown rapidly (practically from scratch) since two months ago such companies as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost the case in the high court of Australia, where they tried to appeal the law.
