UNASUR summit ends without publication of the Lim Declaration
The VI presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the publication of the Lim Declaration, announced earlier and theoretically signed by the family by mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to gain access to the document signed at the 6th meeting of the heads of states and governments of UNASUR, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration pointed out on the main page that it will be transferred after closing, but then confirmed that at some point it will be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they pointed out that the contents were stated by President Peru, Olgat Umal, during brief press statements.
The access of journalists to the information about the Summit was always limited.
During the day it was only broadcast, in the press room, the video of the presidential assembly without sound with the message "closed meeting, the sound is prohibited."
A little information that was circulated among reporters was handed over by the press secretaries of some UNASUR governments present at the meeting, but not Peruvian.
The only document circulated during the day was the list of the Presidents participating, which caused dissatisfaction of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media, who asked for more information.
Subsequently, the presidential administration of Peru sent an electronic message to the media with the "final declaration" of the summit, but it is a statement of Umal, rather than the official document that the summit ended.
Last October, Peru received the III Summit of South American and Arab countries (ASPA), and that time, despite the fact that this insistently demanded the press, was also not distributed the so-called Lim Declaration, which was previously announced.
On the official website of ASPA you can check that the document was published last Tuesday.
During both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure the program systems for all journalists, but to limit the receipt of information as much as possible.
The summit also ended with a joint decision of Chile and Peru to accept the verdict of the Hague Court, which will settle the territorial dispute between both countries.
The Presidents of Peru, Olyanta Umal, and Chile, Sebastian Pinera, gathered at the regional meeting and ratified that they would comply with the International Court of Justice's decision, which will start hearing of both parties" statements on Monday in The Hague, as part of the accusation that Lima put forward against Santiago.
"We will comply with and implement the decision, which will explain the differences that we are currently presenting in this international court," Umala said next to his Chilean colleague.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country respecting international law, a peaceful resolution of disagreements, pacts and international tribunals," said Pinera, and greeted Umal's hand by shaking against the background of the flags of these two countries.
The two presidents confirmed that they would obey the International Court of Justice immediately after Colombia protested this week by the Bogoth Pact, according to which it recognized the submission to the verdicts of this international court after the decision on the sea borders with Nicaragua, which she considered erroneous.
The summit took place in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Roussef; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Christina Kirchner.
The paraguay, whose membership in the UNASUR was suspended since 2011 after the impeachment of its former President Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Olyanta Umal, was responsible for opening discussions in the morning and closing the summit, a little later than noon in Lim time.
The Head of State read the final document, which said that 16 agreements were adopted and directions of action on 31 projects among South American countries were approved, the amount of the estimated investment amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the adopted agreements, he mentioned that the UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the residence agreements."
He said that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against the uncertainty of citizens and against organized transnational crime, actions to increase the availability of drugs, inexpensive Internet access in all parts of South America and taking into account the aggregate and effective risks of natural disasters."
As Europe is in crisis, "the economic union (Latin America) should not have a triumphal basis, but should serve to expand our production basis and foresee a better future for our cities," Umala added.
"We decided to give privileges to a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connection of South American spaces, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes," the Peruvian president said in a read message.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five belong to Peru, and are limited by transverse axes in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at greater ties with Ecuador, but he has not provided more details.
The final document also touched upon the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve as its re-entry to the Union of South American Nations," from which it is now excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace would be united, and had good relations between neighbors, was another topic underline at the summit.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before he started participating in the regional meeting that he hopes to meet his colleague from Nicaragua, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate a respectful way of a naval dispute as a result of the verdict of the international court disputed by Bogota.
"After tomorrow (Saturday), perhaps to meet with President Daniel Ortega," said Santos.
"We will review all these paths, they do not exclude mutually, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua," he stressed.
"I hope I can tell him that we will cope with this as possible civilized and respectful way," Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they have the presence of the new president of this country, Enrique Pena Nieto.
Also within the framework of the summit, the defense ministers of the bloc met in advance to approve the Action Plan for 2013, which aims to strengthen dialogue and unanimity on the issue of protection of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form the UNASUR, although the participation of the latter is suspended.
Peru has a temporary presidency in the regional bloc.
